## Dynamic memory as replay

The dialogue then refined the meaning of memory.

A temporal unit should not store the past as a dead archive. Instead, when a new event arrives, it should trigger a reactivation of the relevant prior event-string.

This led to the claim that memory, in this architecture, is better understood as **dynamic replay**:
- a new event appears
- the unit detects which prior event-string it attaches to
- the prior string is replayed
- the new event is interpreted through how it perturbs that string

This is much stronger than item retrieval.

A good formulation that emerged was:

> Dynamic memory may consist not in storing prior events statically, but in reactivating their corridor when a new event arrives that resonates with them.

This dynamic-memory idea became one of the core features of the temporal unit.

