## Broad replay, itinerancy, and collapse into coherence

The dialogue also explored broad activation and cutoff.

Using an analogy to Tsuda and Kaneko’s itinerant attractors, the temporal unit was imagined as moving through linked choreography strings when a new event arrives.

This gives three phases:

### 1. Ignition
A new event arrives and activates one or more relevant choreography strings.

### 2. Itinerant spread
The temporal unit replays linked strings, spreads through simultaneity families, and explores compatibility, conflict, reinforcement, and possible continuation paths.

### 3. Resonance plateau / collapse
The broad spread narrows when enough active choreographies enter sustained resonance.

This was connected to the idea of “collapse” by analogy to quantum language, though explicitly in a functional rather than physical sense.

The important point was:

> Cutoff occurs when the active choreography field has condensed enough to support commitment.

And in RGPx language:

> The cutoff of broad associative replay may be governed by conservation of coherence: replay continues until the active choreography field settles into a resonance basin that preserves enough coherence to support action, interpretation, or further learning.

This was recognized as a major convergence between the temporal-unit design and the RGPx principle of conservation of coherence.

