## Swarm behavior and local process intelligence

A further simplification came by connecting the temporal unit to swarm logic.

Instead of imagining a centralized temporal master, the unit was increasingly understood as a swarm of simple temporal processes:
- many simple event processes
- each obeying modest rules
- collective behavior expressing PoLA, coherence conservation, and UD cycling

This led to the design principle:

> The temporal unit may be best engineered not as a centralized controller, but as a swarm of simple temporal processes whose collective behavior expresses PoLA, coherence conservation, and UD cycling.

This made the design feel more buildable.

Intelligence here is not imposed from above.
It emerges from:
- local temporal interactions
- local persistence and decay
- local linking and replay
- local simultaneity coupling
- global coherence emerging from distributed dynamics

That was recognized as a strong parallel to the way LLMs themselves achieve complex behavior through simple repeated primitives.

